[ChZDSUhNMG9nS0VJQ0FnSURaLU4tQ1lREAE; reviewBody; """I saw the reviews here and took a chance at staying here, and I entirely understand the wide spectrum in terms of reviewsI'll start by repeating what I've said to numerous people, including employees, family, and friends: you will only be treated with respect if you are coherent, calm, and complacent. All qualities not generally found in a place meant for emergency treatment for mental illnessI suppose I was lucky, with my situation coinciding with those three qualities. I won't discredit anyone's experience here, positive or otherwise, but I personally would not recommend Friends Hospital if you need genuinely anything more than a place to stay away from your current situation and are capable enough to keep yourself safe to a certain degreeWhile I was there, I experienced both ends of the human compassion spectrum, from a technician helping me contact a family member daily, to being flatly ignored when asking for items (such as my daily hygiene bag in the evenings) multiple times. I also experienced medications being given to me that were not prescribed by the psychiatrist, and witnessed emotional and verbal (sometimes physical) abuse between patients and staff alike. I am aware that mental health services as a career is draining and taxing, but I also believe that the career choice should not be taken lightly, especially by those who actively complain that other places offer more money for better hoursIn the hallway, there's a poster that details what a usual day looks like in terms of activities, all on a weekly cycle. Oftentimes, this schedule was not followed. An hour of outdoors time was not offered every day as it should have been, much less actually provided. If we did have groups, they were not done as often as it was supposed to, and the technician-led groups just did not happen. There were two choice instances where the technician-led group time slots were used, but both times were led by patients insteadThe only truly kind and friendly people I encountered were those who did not deal with patients on a constant basis, such as nurses, medical students, social workers, and admin staff. If it weren't for them, I might've done something drastic when I got homeIn all, this was absolutely not the best facility I've stayed at, and I would not recommend it to anyone who isn't excellent at pretending they are fine when at the absolute end of their rope. If you are angry, upset, confused, or anything besides calm and mildly sad, you will be met with disrespect and borderline contempt by the general staff. I truly hope that the hospital takes any and all complaints seriously, as the potential for a healing environment is there, it's just hidden under deep layers of apathy and dismissal."""]

As a simple homeless shelter it is pretty good with  a reasonable food schedule even though if strictly enforced. I would give this a higher score if it was simply a normal homeless shelter but as it is aimed towards younger adults and getting them off the streets they offer little support aside from finding you housing and getting you jobs, in fact they will sometimes enforce times where you cannot enter the building without a job which in my opinion defeats the purpose of getting youth off the street if your restricting them from a safe environment. [Jewish Family and Children's Service of Greater Philadelphia_Our Closet in Your Neighborhood; text; """Our Closet In Your Neighborhood (OCIYN) is a free mobile program that provides basic necessities of food and clothing, as well as access to services and benefits, to families and individuals in need. The bus visits host sites in under-resourced neighborhoods and central locations with fresh, healthy produce and pantry staples, a mini pop-up clothing shop, and an onsite social workerThis program provides:- Food- Clothing- Navigation servicesVisitors receive fresh, locally-sourced produce and pantry staples and are welcome to shop for 10 free, quality items of clothing, shoes, and accessories per person (with a limit of 25 total per family to allow for all to receive what they need). A JFCS social worker is present at every OCIYN event to connect those in need to additional services and benefits for which they may be eligibleOCIYN also provides customized packages of emergency clothing delivered straight to those in need, as well as food package delivery to homebound clientsTo learn more about these services or upcoming pop-up events, contact 267-256-2179 or [email_protected]."""]
[Horizon House_Navigation Center; text; "Navigation Center offers service-resistant homeless individuals the chance to gain stability by offering to meet their immediate needs by providing basic human services.Services include:- Temporary shelter- Food- Showers - Season-appropriate clothing- Resources for other human servicesFor more information, please call the Outreach Coordination Center's 24-hour hotline: 215-232-1984."]
[Merakey - Pennsylvania_Adult Substance Use Disorder Services; text; "Merakey offers comprehensive clinical, evidence-based practice, and therapeutic programs in both community based and clinic based settings to address the impact of addiction on the community, family, and individual.Services Include:- Group, Family, and Individual Counseling- Outpatient and Intensive Outpatient Programs- Drug Free and Medication Assisted Modalities- Co-Occurring Disorders Treatment- Pharmacotherapy Programs- Drug and Alcohol Education- Life Skills Management- Relapse Prevention Planning- Drug ScreeningMerakey accepts Medicaid."]

[Addiction Medicine and Health Advocates Inc_Addiction Medicine And Health Advocates; text; "Addiction Medicine and Health Advocates, Inc. (AMHA) provides evidence-based substance abuse treatment, which is continuously responsive to the needs of the patients and their families. AMHA is an outpatient facility consisting of two levels of care: Outpatient and Intensive Outpatient. Methadone Maintenance is provided on both levels of care.Services provided include: Assessment and intake Medication-assisted treatment (methadone maintenance) Individual counseling & psychotherapy Group psychotherapy Psycho education Medical & psychiatric evaluations  Aftercare & follow up services  Referrals (educational, medical, vocational, psychiatric, higher levels of care) Couples & family therapy Drug screening To begin the admissions process, please contact us. You may also come in person between the hours of 9 am and 4 pm, Monday through Friday. You will be asked to complete a short screening interview and if initial eligibility criteria is met, you will be scheduled for an assessment.At the time of your assessment, you will need to bring: Current, state-issued photo ID Insurance cardAMHA is a private not-for-profit organization dependent upon patient fees for its continuance. Most of our patients have some form of insurance or medical assistance that pays for medication-assisted treatment services. Individuals who do not have insurance are responsible for payment or they may be eligible for county funding."]

[SELF Inc_Station House Intake Center Services; text; "Centralized Homeless Intake Services includes an assessment of eligibility and service needs of persons and families presenting for placement into emergency housing. If eligible, persons and families are placed in appropriate emergency housing, boarding homes, or other alternative housing. Services include:- Temporary shelter- Ongoing case management services- Assistance with obtaining transitional and/or permanent housing- Supportive housing for special populations- An optional savings program which allows households to save a part of their income for future housing expensesMental health assessments and referrals to drug/alcohol treatment, health services, children and youth services, legal services and veteran's services, etc., are provided as needed to clients of the program.- Connecting Services to other community resources- ScreeningIf you are currently experiencing homelessness, please call us during business hours. You must go through central intake for an initial assessment of your housing needs before placement into the homeless housing system."]

[Women In Transition_Substance Abuse Intervention; text; "Substance Abuse Intervention is not a 12-step program, nor is it faith-based, however, we are respectful of each individual's spirituality. We do not require drug tests, but we do ask that you refrain from using drugs or alcohol before you come to your counseling or group sessions.Services Include:- Empowerment counseling for recoveryOur service model recognizes that change and recovery are a process and integrates the concepts of harm reduction into trauma-informed empowerment so that we can better address both relationship violence and substance abuse. Our safe and supportive services help women increase self-esteem and personal awareness about practical issues which are key to a woman's recovery. Services are free and confidential. For more information call 215-751-1111."]

[Conquerors Community Development Corporation_Various Community Events and Programs; text; "The Conquerors Community Development Corporation (CCDC) hosts Various Community Events & Programs that help to elevate the quality of life for the West and Southwest Philadelphia communities.  We host the 51st Ward Register Community Organization (RCO) Mondays 6pm-8pm and a number of other Community engagement events throughout the year with the following being held annually:1) Community Health Fair - A host of healthcare agencies provide access to a wide-range of information and services for our neighbors.2) Back 2 School Community Day - The CCDC partners with Victory Christian Center for our back-to-school event which includes refreshments, activities and entertainment for kids, parents and guardians. We provide information about programs and services for children, new backpacks, and school supplies.3) Senior Thanksgiving Luncheon - In partnership with the United Block Captains Association (UBCA) and Victory Christian Center, we host a Thanksgiving Dinner style luncheon for the senior in the neighborhood.4) Christmas at Victory Village - Through our annual Toy Drive at Victory Christian Center and with Coats received from the YMCA in partnership with Auto Dealers CARing for Kids Foundation, we provide a new coat, a toy, and book for children in need. This is a festive and lively event that includes food, music and entertainment for families during the holiday season."]

[The Attic Youth Center_Mental Health Counseling; text; "The Counseling Department of The Attic Youth Center provides counseling services to LGBTQ youth and young adults and their families/caregivers (biological or by choice). This service uses an LGBTQ affirmative and strength based approach that it is contextual, developmental and culturally sensitive.  This program provides: - Individual therapy- Group therapy- Family and couples therapyThe Attic's clinical team is skilled in addressing a variety of challenges including:- Coming out- Gender questions- Problems at school- Depression and anxiety- Trauma and PTSD- Sexual abuse- Substance abuse- Violence and domestic violence- Anger management- Immigration transitions- Developmental delays- Behavioral and family dynamics as related to the LGBTQ experienceAll Attic counselors and therapists are masters or PhD level and have significant experience working with LGBTQ youth.  To inquire about counseling or to make an appointment, please call The Attic's counseling line and leave a confidential voicemail message with your name and the best way to reach you. A staff member will return your call. You can also reach out by email.All counseling services are currently virtual."]
[Hispanic Community Counseling Services_Adult Outpatient Services; text; "The Adult Outpatient Services provide assessment, diagnosis, and treatment to individuals requiring mental health or dual diagnosis treatment (treatment of mental health plus substance use). The outpatient treatment team consists of trained professionals including psychiatrists, licensed therapists, psychiatric technicians, counselors, and support staff. Focus areas include mental health and substance use assessment, psychiatric assessment and evaluation for medication, medication monitoring, limited individual counseling, group counseling, bilingual counseling services, interpreter services, benefits services, and community services referral.Common diagnoses for clients at HCCS include disorders of mood, anxiety, personality, addiction and psychosis. HCCS currently offers the following services within the traditional outpatient menu of services:- Psychiatric Evaluation- Medication Managemen- Individual Counseling- Family Therapy- Group Therapy- Psychological Testing and evaluation- Co-occurring Services - Mobile Therapy - Perinatal Depression Treatment servicesHispanic Community Counseling Services accepts Medicare and Medicaid."]

[Covenant House Pennsylvania_Youth Services; text; "Covenant House Pennsylvania offers shelter and supportive services to young people experiencing homelessness. They aim to help homeless young people become healthy, happy, responsible, productive, and ultimately independent adults.This program provides:- A safe, secure environment- Immediate and transitional housing- Rapid rehousing- Meals and food- Case Management- Spiritual Support- Counseling- Physical health, mental health, and drug and alcohol services- Saving and budgeting- Continuing education- Support for LGBTQ individuals- Job readinessThe Crisis Center is open 24 hours per day, seven days per week. There are no shelter fees, however, those staying at the shelter must deposit 75% of their income during their stay. All money is returned upon leaving the shelter. Covenant House is a drug and weapon-free program."]

[Youth Service Inc_Youth Emergency Service; text; "Youth Emergency Service (YES) offers immediate housing, respite, and support services to youth ages 12-17 facing housing insecurity or are unable to safely live with family. YES Services include:- Twenty four hour emergency respite and protection for youth ages 12-17- Telephone hotline and referral services as well as links to national runaway and homeless youth providers through national Runaway Safeline and National safe Place- Medical care _ examinations and follow-up- Counseling supports and referrals- Voluntary and confidential HIV testing- Linkage to The Attic for those wanting service for LGBTQ youth- Physical and sexual health information and supports- Referral to home based services for families- Education and recreation programming and supports- Title I tutoringYouth can be self referred, enter through the formal child welfare system, Department of Human Services, or through referrals from partner organizations throughout the county. Referrals come from family, school staff and other concerned persons."]

Our residents continue their individual journey of recovery in a live in/ work out environment, with the support and structure of staff and peers to provide an opportunity for continued success. Of greatest importance is maintaining the established in-house recovery support network and gradually extending this into the larger non-treatment community through 12 Step Fellowship meeting attendance, faith-based community worship, social visits with family and sober friends. Available treatments address all types of problems related to substance use, from unhealthy use of alcohol to life-threatening addictions.This program provides:- First-time screening for alcohol or tobacco use in all care locations- Short outpatient counseling including focus on motivation- Intensive outpatient treatment- Residential (live-in) care- Medically managed detoxification (stopping substance use safely) and services to get stable- Continuing care and relapse prevention- Marriage and family counseling- Self-help groups- Drug substitution therapies and newer medicines to reduce cravingDecisions as to which services are provided and how intense they are will be based on the patient's needs and desires.All veterans are encouraged to enroll in the VA Health Care System. To begin the process, please complete an Application for Health Care Benefits. You can submit the form online, or you may print the form to be mailed or brought to your local VA medical center or clinic."]
